261
00:14:00.060 --> 00:14:02.060
and it's very good for everyday work.

262
00:14:02.060 --> 00:14:04.060
It's not quite as sensitive,

263
00:14:04.060 --> 00:14:19.870
if you don't have super precise notes,

264
00:14:19.870 --> 00:14:22.870
and above all, under low loads,

265
00:14:22.870 --> 00:14:24.870
they tend to shrink a bit.

266
00:14:24.870 --> 00:14:25.870
That means,

267
00:14:25.870 --> 00:14:30.670
when the paraglider is naturally flying,

268
00:14:30.670 --> 00:14:35.670
it has roughly 80% of the total load on the A and B riser groups,

269
00:14:35.670 --> 00:14:40.670
and at the back, on the C or D riser groups, the remaining 20% is.

270
00:14:40.670 --> 00:14:42.670
That naturally means,

271
00:14:42.670 --> 00:14:45.670
if you build the lines into the C and D area,

272
00:14:45.670 --> 00:14:47.670
which get less loaded,

273
00:14:47.670 --> 00:14:50.670
and the (unclear)

274
00:14:50.670 --> 00:14:52.670
the (unclear).

275
00:14:52.670 --> 00:14:54.670
Then we have the wing shrinking there.

276
00:14:54.670 --> 00:14:57.790
The others, by brand,

277
00:15:20.480 --> 00:15:23.480
you have to look carefully where you build them in.

278
00:15:23.480 --> 00:15:27.480
Because, naturally, when there's a part on the wing

279
00:15:27.480 --> 00:15:30.480
where, as you say, it now gets loaded,

280
00:15:30.480 --> 00:15:35.480
then it's important that they're insensitive there

281
00:15:35.480 --> 00:15:40.480
to kinking or to length stability.

282
00:15:40.480 --> 00:15:44.480
That's why it's always a mix between the aramid lines

283
00:15:44.480 --> 00:15:47.480
and the Dyneema lines,

284
00:15:47.480 --> 00:15:49.480
you say with the upper area,

285
00:15:49.480 --> 00:15:51.480
probably more the Dyneema inside,

286
00:15:51.480 --> 00:15:53.480
the lower aramid lines,

287
00:15:53.480 --> 00:15:55.480
to simply get the best mix possible,

288
00:16:18.480 --> 00:16:21.480
very good.
